Time of Flight(TOF) sensor:



A Time-of-Flight (ToF) sensor is a type of proximity and depth-sensing device that measures distance by calculating how long it takes for emitted light 
(typically infrared laser pulses) to travel to an object and reflect back to the sensor.
The fundamental principle is straightforward: 
since the speed of light is constant,
the sensor can precisely determine the distance to an object by measuring this round-trip time, often down to millimeter-level accuracy. 
Unlike traditional ultrasonic sensors that use sound waves, ToF sensors use light, making them significantly faster, more accurate,
and capable of working across a wider range of distances — typically from a few centimeters up to several meters.
In embedded systems and robotics projects pushed to GitHub, ToF sensors like the VL53L0X or VL53L1X (by STMicroelectronics) are extremely popular. 
They communicate over I2C, making integration with microcontrollers like Arduino, ESP32, or Raspberry Pi straightforward.
When you push a ToF sensor project to GitHub, your repository would typically include the sensor driver or library (e.g., Adafruit's VL53L0X library),
initialization and configuration code, the main sensing loop that reads distance values, and any application logic built on top — such as obstacle detection, 
gesture recognition, or level measurement. A good GitHub repo for a ToF sensor project would also contain a clear README.md explaining wiring diagrams,
dependencies, and how to run the code, making it easy for others to replicate your setup.
